Holly Krambeck  2  The   Lab   integrate s   modern data analytics in Bank lending, technical assistance,  and economic monitoring programs by connecting   operations teams to data  resources, managing external data partnerships with firms and universities on  behalf of all staff, organizing training and upskilling opportunities,   creating and  advocating for coding standards and   supporting   their implementation, and  producing   a library   reusable code and data products .   The   Lab is entirely self -  funded through its programs.   For a complete list of   activities, see intranet site:  https://datalab.worldbank.org .  Open   Transport   Data   Program .   Designed, raised funds for, and led program to  provide technical assistance to transport agencies on improving the efficiency  and efficacy of transport data collection, management, and analysis for decision  making .   The program included :  •   Open - Source National Road Crash Data Platform .   L ed the  development and implementation of an open - source national road  incident recording and analysis application, which has been translated  into eight languages and signed into legislation in the Philippines as  the national crash reporting system.  •   Rural Road Investment Prioritization Application .   L ed the  development of an open - source application for rural accessibility  mapping   –   generating statistics on the percentage of villagers who  can access select points of interest within   x   minutes by road,  accompanied by travel - shed isochrones maps. To date, the system  has been used to support Bank lending projects in China, Laos,  Vietnam, Peru, and Argentina.  •   Transit System Mapping and Database Creation .   L ed the development  of a methodology and suite of open - source software applications  based on international open data and standards. These solutions have  enabled the low - cost production of transit maps and databases,  empowering transit agencies to make plann ing and investment  decisions based on comprehensive transit data. This approach has  been adopted in Bank projects in China, Philippines, Vietnam,   Mexico,  Sierra   Leone, and others.  •   The Open Transport Data Partnership .   L ed a pilot program in the  Philippines, leveraging taxi GPS data to develop methods for  improving the efficiency and efficacy of data collection for transport  planning, as well as a suite of applications for using these data to  inform decision - making. After   initial success, expanded the pilot to  establish a Partnership program, including private companies Grab  and Easy Taxi:   http://bit.ly/38cY66I .   The Open Transport Partnership  has since been spun out as an independent non - profit entit y,  continuing to support use of third - party mobility data to derive  insights for governments.:

Feedback for Developmental Assignment
Feedback Provider: Amy Jean Doherty, Vice President & WBG Chief Information Officer; ITSVP
Date: May 1, 2025

It was such a pleasure to have Holly Krambeck join the ITS leadership team on DAIS this year. Holly brought us a very fresh perspective and built awareness and empathy for some of our most critical users of technology in IBRD. She was so helpful in building bridges between DEC and ITS by pointing out ways in which ITS could be a stronger collaborator and better partner. Within ITS, she instilled new processes and discipline by examining data and observing behaviors. As a result, her suggestions were well received and very productive. Her engagement style is welcoming and inclusive. She was able to continuously scan our work program and environment for issues and risks, and her engagement style broke down barriers and silos. I valued Holly's advice as she coached me on the culture of WBG. As a new leader, her insights about personalities, power structures and protocols was essential training for me! I greatly appreciated the value that she created on her DAIS and hope that she received
equal value in the exchange.
FY25 OPE Feedback  Request Summary (Anonymous)

Anonymous (Peer): Holly has been a great colleague to collaborate with on the work related to LLM in Malawi. She planned her project well in advance, engaging both with the country office and with the various practices that were directly or tangentially connected to the work she was about to undertake. She is highly adaptable to the country's circumstances, program needs, and evolving priorities.  She successfully coordinated a mission to align with the engagement of the Poverty Practice and ensured it took place at the same time they were working with the Government—specifically with the NSO of Malawi. She introduced the initiative to the country office and then joined the practice team in visiting the client. This approach was very well received, as it presented the World Bank as a unified institution rather than working in silos.  Holly is very thoughtful about cultural differences. With respect and even some knowledge of the local language, she quickly built rapport with the client

. I also observed that she is highly technical, efficient, and attentive to corporate requirements, including legal aspects necessary for moving forward with her work. In addition, she is a strong leader. I could see how she built on existing efforts, recognizing the skills and contributions of her peers and colleagues, and integrating her work as a complement rather than as a standalone input. Lastly, she is kind, warm, always smiling, and treats you first as a person, then as a professional.

Anonymous (Peer): I've had the pleasure of collaborating with Holly, both at WB data lab and over the past six months of the DAIS at ITSVP. She's been instrumental in building strong data partnerships—raising the Innovation Office's profile across the WBG community, connecting teams for impactful projects, and co-organizing DATA Mixers that brought together nearly 80 colleagues to spark new collaborations. Her supportive leadership and deep expertise in data and AI trends shine through in every discussion, and she consistently guides us with clarity and vision. I'm grateful for her steady encouragement and look forward to what we'll achieve together in FY26.

Anonymous (Peer): I would like to recognize Holly for her outstanding contributions and collaborative spirit across multiple initiatives, including our work together in the CIO's front office and the successful launch of the AQ Monitors Installation Project across WBG offices. Her project coordination skills and commitment to teamwork were evident throughout.  Beyond her strong subject matter expertise, she brought forward innovative ideas and demonstrated exceptional initiative in establishing partnerships with both internal and external stakeholders—efforts that were instrumental in moving the AQ project forward. What stands out most is her strong expertise and deep commitment to the WBG mission, which is truly inspirational. On a personal note, I am especially grateful for the way she made me feel included and valued as part of the team and a key contributor for the AQ project, through her encouragement and thoughtful advice. I look forward to more opportunities to working together
with Holly in the future!

Anonymous (Peer): Holly is a solid member of DEC, developing unique innovations to its portfolio of work and providing great feedback to other team members. She has led on a range of important initiatives or provided important inputs to much of the scale up of DG that are admirable, and for which the whole department owes her a debt. On a personal level, she is a thoroughly nice person to work with and I really enjoy having her as a colleague.  In the year to come, Holly could develop her leadership role even more than she has to date, and forge towards her next step at DEC or within the wider Bank more clearly. She could be a great leader in her field, and it will be exciting to see her grow towards that role. A key part of this is institutionalizing her work broadly within DG, DEC and the wider Bank. Beyond her own capabilities, identifying how to sustain the innovations she has led will be of benefit to DEC and the world.

Anonymous (Other): Holly was my mentor this fiscal year, and I can truly say that her perspective has helped me approach challenges and opportunities in new and more thoughtful ways. I've had the chance to be part of many of the meetings she leads, and her leadership style is one that I deeply admire, she leads with authenticity, clear intention, and forward-thinking. She brings a genuine passion for improving how we do our work, consistently challenging the status quo and asking, "How can we do better?" rather than settling for "This is how we've always done it." She creates space for new ideas, encourages innovation, and leads with a clear sense of purpose and integrity. It was a real pleasure learning from her this year, and I'm incredibly grateful for her mentorship and example. I look forward to keep learning from her.

Anonymous (Peer): Holly, what can I say? I just got to know you this past year as part of the Data Scientist workshops. From day one you could tell how dedicated and knowledgeable you were. The workshops broke down barriers that have been up for years between ITS and the BU. Thank you for making that happen and allowing me to use our teams skills to work to make a difference. We are just in the beginning stages but with a partner like you we will be able to solve some problems and have some fun along the way!

Anonymous (Peer): Holly has always and continues to be amazing to work with. She has deep technical expertise and has a keen pulse on innovations in data - and has had notable impact in ensuring the Bank keeps at the cutting edge. One of the things I appreciate most about Holly is that her work elevates those of others - whether this be through the DDP elevating the types of data the Bank has access to, to working to ensure data scientists + others have the technical support they need to do their work best. On top of all this, Holly is wonderfully nice and a joy to work with. Looking forward to continued collaboration into the next FY.

Anonymous (Direct/Indirect Report): Holly is an extremely hardworking and dedicated leader who consistently sets a strong example for the team. Her commitment to the work, responsiveness, and willingness to go above and beyond are constant and highly value. Holly brings a lot of energy and drive to everything she does, and her advocacy for our team's work is remarkable. I also value her openness to new ideas and her constant support. While Holly has many ideas and projects in mind for the team, the volume of these sometimes feel overwhelming without clear direction. A more strategic approach would help the team better understand which ideas to prioritize and when to take action. Additionally, I believe there is an opportunity to be more selective and intentional when commniting to projects. I appreciate Holly's dedication for the team's wellbeing and constant support to help everyone grown professionally.

Anonymous (Peer): Holly is inspiring to work with. She consistently builds strategic coalitions, brokering cooperation amongst various units/teams and with diverse range of clients that secure stakeholder buy-ins. She engages counterparts with nuance and realistic delivery milestones when navigating new ventures and novel areas of Bank work. She has great technical knowledge/background which improves the quality of legal deliverables through her feedback. Her leadership positions the Bank as leading the charge in various innovative initiatives, while reinforcing the Bank's various governance principles and policy objectives. It's been a pleasure to work with her and I look forward to supporting her and her team as she replicates her success and amplify institutional impact.

Anonymous (Peer): Holly is the most effective and principled Task Team Leader I have worked with. She leads by example, setting a consistently high standard through her own work ethic, discipline, and attention to detail. Her leadership reflects a deep commitment not only to the substance of the work, but also to its institutional impact and long-term development value. What sets Holly apart is her integrity and the care she brings to every aspect of project delivery—from technical content to team coordination to client engagement. She does not treat TTL responsibilities as procedural or transactional; she internalizes the stakes, owns the outcomes, and invests in the people she works with. It is rare to encounter a TTL who balances strategic direction, operational rigor, and genuine team leadership so seamlessly. Holly's example raises the bar for everyone around her.

INDIVIDUAL BUSINESS OBJECTIVES
Connect
Goal: Expand internal and external data collaboration opportunities through the Development Data Partnership, University Data Fellows, and Data Lab Community.

Results: We exceeded targets while delivering high-impact institutional outcomes. Development Data Partnership membership grew by four new partners (Grab Maps, QuantCube, VesselBot, Constellr), doubling our annual goal. We secured a Gates Foundation grant for AI model training data access, earning a VPU Team Award and the Legal VPU's sole President's Innovation Award nomination. The University Data Fellows training reached 40+ students, doubling our target. Despite sunsetting the Lab event branding, we maintained community engagement through seven major events, each drawing a wide range of participants, including flagship convenings like the AI Roundtable (11 international organizations, 5 AI companies) and Development Data Partnership Day (180 in-person, 275 virtual attendees). We also launched a cross-departmental air quality monitoring initiative spanning DEC, Planet, ITS, HSD, and GCS, with expanding partnerships to UNDP and UNICEF.
Scale
Goal: Scale data science methods adoption through best practices advocacy, certification programs, cross-support systems, and reusable tools.

Results: We exceeded support targets, assisting 18 projects despite team capacity constraints. Key achievements include 45 operational projects adopting our standardized template, five reusable code packages deployed, and a GitHub-based project management system implemented. The data skills certification program is fully developed and ready for FY26 launch. As part of my DAIS, I launched the Data Analytics Day 1 initiative, uniting three ITS directors and eight managers across Treasury, IEG, IFC, DEC, and Operations to address data science resource access barriers. This yielded immediate results: a $64K laptop pilot, ITS subscription to a new developer portal, a special self-service software center for data scientists that has been deployed on staff PCs, and a beta institution-wide information portal now accepting inputs from the WBG data community.
Plan
Goal: Establish foundation for code.worldbank.org formalization and DAIS system development.

Results: While DECDG reorganization has required an adjustment to these panning activities, we secured tentative funding and ITS support for code.worldbank.org through the AIP process, ensuring continuity regardless of organizational changes. The platform will integrate with the Development Data Partnership for cross-organization code sharing. The ‘Data DAIS’ initiative will be reimagined in FY26, as an opportunity for staff to get hands-on experience working with Partnership data and code.

Criteria: Creative problem-solving approach with passion for delivering meaningful outcomes.
My approach to problem-solving combines technical innovation with deep understanding of user needs to create solutions that address real-world challenges. When faced with the Philippines' lack of comprehensive crash data, I didn't simply digitize existing processes—I developed an entirely open-source platform that could be adapted globally, resulting in legislative adoption and translation into eight languages. Similarly, recognizing that traditional transit mapping was prohibitively expensive for developing cities, I created a methodology using international open data standards that enabled low-cost production of comprehensive transit databases. This approach – creating innovative programs with scaling as an objective from the beginning – is also being used in my current $1.5 million Gates Foundation project to scale national digital low-resource language libraries for AI model training.  My passion for meaningful outcomes drives me to ensure solutions are sustainable and scalable: the Data Lab and the Development Data Partnership operate as entirely self-funded. This creative approach consistently transforms technical challenges into opportunities for systemic impact, always keeping the end goal of development effectiveness at the center of innovation efforts.
